author: @digitalambience6993
text: For those confused on what the heck is going on with the .gitignore file: - the .gitignore file is a hidden file. This is why when listing (using ls) we have to include the -a flag or -la to show the long-form list of all files - visible and hidden. (Same applies to the .git directory) - When you navigate to the actual folder/directory in Finder (or whatever the equivanlent is on PC) where this .gitignore file is stored, you wont see it unless you press Shift + Command + . (<-- note the period). This key command reveals these hidden files in the Finder window and you will see that .gitignore file. Then you can open it and add the file names of the files you want git to ignore. To do this literally just type the names of the files with their extensions into this document and save. If you want you can hide the hidden files again within the Finder window by pressing Shift + Command + . once more. - After doing this it will work just as it does in the vid.  - Also if you want to remove files from the .gitignore just open the .gitignore file and, that's right, you guessed it, delete the names of those files and save. Now those files will be available once again in the working directory and visible when you run the git status command.  Hope this helps!

author: @omarfaruqeriyad6707
text: In 20:30, if you are having a Git push error '[remote rejected] master -> master (branch is currently checked out)'  then  what is happening is that you have two repositories, one is the original you first made, and the other the work one you just made.  Right now you are in your work repository and are using the "master" branch. But you also happen to be "logged in" in your original repository to the same "master" branch.  Now since you're "logged in" in the original, Git fears you might mess up because you might be  working on the original and screw things up. So you need to return to the original repository and do a "git checkout someotherbranch", and now you can push with no problems.    https://stackoverflow.com/a/2933656/14327056

author: @Jasond7595
text: Hi, just in case ill leave it here) If you find any mistakes, please leave a comment)  1) Create branch: 	$ git branch coconut 2) Switcheng to a new branch (aka coconut): 	$ git checkout coconut  3) Make changes/ work in the branch  4) Check for branch modification: 	$ git status 5) Add changes to staging directory: 	$ git add -A 5) Commit chancges: 	$ git commit -m "THE COCONUT HAS BEEN CRACKED" 6) Push branch to remote repository: 	$ git push -u origin coconut 7) Merge with master: 	$ git checkout master 	$ git pull origin master 	$ git merge coconut 8) Push changes to the remote repository 	$ git push origin master 9) Delete branch:         $ git branch -d ‚Äúbranch name‚Äù                     ‚Äî delete from local         $ git push origin ‚Äîdelete ‚Äúbranch name‚Äù   ‚Äî delete from remote

author: @3_2_1Delete
text: Very informative video Corey. Here is a copy of my notes  you may find it useful.  Git Command Line Fundamentals Notes    install git from git-scm.com   git ‚Äìversion = check git version git config ‚Äìglobal user.name ‚ÄúName‚Äù = declare username variable git config ‚Äìglobal user.email ‚ÄúEmail address‚Äù = declare user e-mail variable  git config ‚Äìlist = lists configuration values   git help <verb> =help 1  git <verb> --help  = both syntax for get help  git init = intitialises project directory tracking  git status = check tracking statuses of files  touch .gitignore = creates file to ignore tracking of specified files  *.pyc = starring a file ignores all files with specified extension type  git add -A = add files to the staging area  git reset <filename>= remove specified from the staging area  git reset = remove everything from the staging area  cd = change directory  ls -la = lists directory, lists all in directory  How to commit files to git repository. git add -A =add everything to the staging area  git commit -m ‚Äúcomment a message for your commit‚Äù git status = check the status of your repo git log = check hash number, author and message of commit  How to track an existing remote project with git   git clone <url> <location> = clones a remote repository  git clone ../remote_repo.git using a period at the end of url saves it to current repository  How to view information about the remote repository  git remote -v = lists repository information, location on local machine etc. git branch -a = lists branches in repository                How to commit changes to the remote repository:  Make change to code and save it.  git diff = view changes that have been made within the code  git status = view modified file git add -A = adds modified repository to the staging area  git status = displays modified repository information in the staging area  git commit -m ‚ÄúCommenting on changes made within code‚Äù  git pull origin master = pulls any changes that have been made by other devs within the repository since last pull  git push origin master = pushes recent changes from local repository to remote repository   How to create a branch for desired feature additions  git branch <title> = changes the branch you are working on  git branch = displays the currently selected branch  git status = displays modified file  git add -A = adds changes to staging  git commit -m ‚ÄúCommenting on edited code.‚Äù The change has now been saved to the local branch of the name listed in command 1.  How to push the branch to the remote repository  git push -u origin <branch title> = push branch to the remote repository  git branch -a = displays branch info within remote and local repositories   How to merge a branch with master   git checkout master = switches to master branch  git pull origin master = pulls changes made since last pull  git branch ‚Äìmerged = tells us the branches we have merged to master so far git merge <branchname> =merges the specified branch with master  git push origin master = pushes merge changes to master branch on remote repo  How to delete a branch git branch ‚Äìmerged = displays previously merged branches  git branch -d <branchname> = deletes branch locally  git branch -a = displays local and remote repo contents  git push origin ‚Äìdelete <branchname> = deletes the specified branch from the remote repository

author: @alexradu1921
text: So I've taken some notes for the last "fast example" of the video (the one that concludes all the commands). So, here is the workflow you will repeat forever from now on:  git config --global user.name git config --global user.email git clone <url> <where_to_clone> git branch my_new_branch git checkout my_new_branch (make changes to the code) git status git commit -m "Add @function in file7" git push -u origin my_new_branch (wait for unit tests to complete) (if all unit tests pass, then do these) git checkout master git pull origin master git merge my_new_branch git push origin master (now time to delete my_new_branch) git branch -d my_new_branch git branch -a git push origin --delete my_new_branch

author: @Debazed
text: Great tutorial, thank you. I found it on the Odin Project! Here my markdown notes with the commands shown in the tutorial (feel free to correct mistakes, please):  3:50 ## CHECK VERSION ```git --version```  _______  4:20 ## SET CONFIG VALUES ```git config --global user.name "Your Name"```  ```git config --global user.email "Your Email"```  ### GET CURRENT CONFIG VALUES ```git config --list```  ______  5:40 ## NEED HELP? ```git help config``` ```git config --help```  ______  7:00 ## INITIALIZE A REPO FROM EXISTING CODE ```git init```  ______  8:40 ## BEFORE FIRST COMMIT ```git status```  ______  12:00 ## ADD FILES TO STAGING AREA  ### ALL FILES IN CURRENT DIRECTORY ```git add -A```  ### SPECIFIC FILE ```git add foobar.py```  ______  13:00 ## REMOVE FILES FROM THE STAGING AREA ```git reset foobar.py```  ______  13:30 ## OUR FIRST COMMIT ```git add -A``` ```git commit -m "This is a message describing the commit"```  ### CHECK OUT WHAT IS GOING ON ```git status``` ```git log```  ______  15:10 ## CLONING A REMOTE REPO ### FROM AN URL ```git clone <url_to_clone_from> <path_where_to_clone_on_your_machine>```  ### FROM A PATH ON YOUR LOCAL MACHINE ```git clon <path_from_where_to_clone> <path_where_to_clone>```  ______  17:05 ## VIEW INFO ABOUT THE REMOTE REPO ```git remote -v``` ```git branch -a```  ______  18:30 ## PUSHING CHANGES ### CHECK CHANGES YOU'VE MADE TO THE CODE ```git diff```  ### MAKE A COMMIT ```git status``` ```git add -A``` ```git commit -m "This is a commit"```  ### FIRST: MAKE SURE YOU PULL THE LATEST VERSION OF THE CODE FROM REMOTE REPO (origin is the name of the repository, master is the branch from which we want to pull) ```git pull origin master```  ### THEN: PUSH YOUR CHANGES ```git push origin master```  ______  21:10 ## COMMON WORKFLOW ### CREATE A BRANCH FOR DESIRED NEW FEATURE ```git branch <local_branch_name>```  ```git checkout <local_branch_name>```  ### MAKE A COMMIT (SAME AS 13:30)  ### PUSH LOCAL BRANCH TO REMOTE REPO ```git push -u origin <local_branch_name>```  ### VIEW THE BRANCHES ```git branch -a```  ### SWITCH TO REMOTE REPO MASTER BRANCH ```git checkout master```  ### PULL THE LATEST VERSION OF THE CODE ```git pull origin master```  ### CHECK THE BRANCHES THAT HAVE BEEN MERGED INTO MASTER SO FAR ```git branch --merged```  ### MERGE A BRANCH ```git merge <local_branch_name>```  ```git push origin master```

author: @CrippleX89
text: I agree that at some point it will be important to know how to work with git command line *however* I strongly disagree that learning git CLI should be the first step into git. When you first start learning about git, it's very important to get to know the very basics: what's staging, what's a commit, what are branches, merging and rebasing (I know rebasing is frowned upon by some, but you should at least know what it is, right?), what do fetch, pull and push conceptually do? All that kind of good stuff; and the GUI tools that are available can really help to visualize what's going on and what impact your actions have. Without visualization, it's much harder to see what you're doing. Only when you really understand the concepts of git, the GUI tools might start to limit you. However, even that should not stop you from using the GUI tools; at this point you should ask yourself which you personally prefer: GUI or CLI.  I like to mix both: use GUI for the basic tasks and CLI only when I need to do things that the GUI tools that I use don't offer. GUI tools that I would recommend is of course Source Tree because it's free of charge and Fork (fork.dev) because it's a much cleaner UI and less annoying in terms of workflow but does cost some money after the free trial.

author: @danhaas5933
text: Help please *edit: solved, solution below.* ...trying to follow along while practicing with repositiories on my own github account.  When I try git pull <repository name> <branch>, I get an error saying "fatal: '<repository name>' does not appear to be a git repository" "fatal: could not read from remote repository." "Please make sure you have the correct access rights and the repository exists".  I'm logged into the terminal as the github repository owner, so I must have access rights.  The repository exists, I know because I successfully cloned it just like in the video. Please share your advice! *solution:* i was incorrectly writing only the repository name as <repository name> but it needs to be the full repository URL.  ex: "git pull Repository1 master" won't work, but "git pull https://github.com/username/Repository1 master" will work.

author: @gregtuve1109
text: Wow.  This is so abstract from the perspective of a rookie, and yet, so clear.  Why?  Corey uses the simplest possible examples at every step, has code ready to change, makes the simplest possible changes, explains everything he is doing, often before he does it and again after he does it.  He does not race through everything, hoping to show us how fast or easy some system is or how clever he is.  It's so clear, I was able to deduce some properties of git that he didn't even tackle in his exposition.  I absolutely agree with Adrian Wilk:  Go through the entire video even if you plan to work with git only locally.  No matter what you're doing, take the time to study every video CS makes that has any bearing on your goals.  NOBODY DOES IT BETTER.  Theres no FOO or BAR here.  Instead he names the remote repository "origin" to clarify git's checkout and push commands, showing file changes at every step with appropriate commands.  Most of the explanatory video on the web is too basic for me now.  Why?  BECAUSE OF COREY SHAFER.  Good morning Corey!  I sure could use a video on using slightly advanced query objects in Django to work with related tables.  I'm raising your monthly stipend 50%.

author: @Eganstan
text: For those who run into a problem - understand that cloning a remote repo or using the $ git init command will MAKE A FOLDER  inside your current working directory that is HIDDEN. It is called .git. If you run into some sort of weird problem try going into your file explorer and showing hidden files (ctrl H on Ubuntu, maybe something different on other OS's). Delete the .git folder. This will allow you to "start over". Might help, might not, but finding this out helped me conceive what was actually going on.
